(1820, 62, 0, 514, 'Pink opal is a natural gemstone found in the Andes mountains in Peru. Pink opals are thought to foster inspiration, imagination and creativity, and to symbolize love and kindness. \r\n\r\nThis strand of round 14 mm opal beads is beautifully cut and simply knotted with a 10 mm 14K white gold ball clasp to create a very elegant alternative to a traditional strand of pearls. \r\n\r\nThis strand is approximately 17 inches long.'),
(1821, 61, 0, 515, 'Lapis lazuli has been mined in Afghanistan for millennia. Lapis is composed of a mixture of minerals, the most prominent of which is lazurite, with veining of calcite (white) and pyrite (gold). \r\n\r\nI bought several significant strands of lapis a few years ago and put them away, planning to string them one at a time. I\'m really glad I did because the lapis fields have since become contentious, with many gemmologists (including me) considering lapis mined recently to be a conflict mineral because of the role revenue from lapis mining is currently playing in financing the Taliban. It is very important to me that all of my lapis was sourced from what I believe to be reputable sources prior to this escalation.\r\n\r\nThis strand is made up of approximately 20 mm lapis beads knotted with a 20 mm sterling silver box clasp. The length is approximately 17 inches. '),
(1822, 62, 0, 515, 'Lapis lazuli has been mined in Afghanistan for millennia. Lapis is composed of a mixture of minerals, the most prominent of which is lazurite, with veining of calcite (white) and pyrite (gold). This strand is made up of approximately 20 mm lapis beads knotted with a 20 mm sterling silver box clasp. The length is approximately 17 inches. '),
(1823, 61, 0, 516, 'When I look at landscape jasper, I feel like I have a window into the secrets of the earth. These landscape jasper beads have a matte finish that I just love. \r\n\r\nLandscape jasper is said to create harmony, and I certainly think it exudes a feeling of grounded peacefulness and a connection to the earth. Each strand of jasper has different colour overtones, so each is unique.\r\n\r\nThis necklace is approximately 21 inches long and is made from landscape jasper beads that are approximately 16 mm in diameter and finished with a sterling silver spring ring. '),
(1824, 62, 0, 516, 'When I look at landscape jasper, I feel like I have a window into the secrets of the earth. These landscape jasper beads have a matte finish that I just love. \r\n\r\nLandscape jasper is said to create harmony, and I certainly think it exudes a feeling of grounded peacefulness and a connection to the earth. Each strand of jasper has different colour overtones, so each is unique.\r\n\r\nThis necklace is approximately 21 inches long and is made from landscape jasper beads that are approximately 16 mm in diameter and finished with a sterling silver spring ring. '),
(1825, 61, 0, 517, 'The necktie probably entered into fashion history as a result of the 30 year war in France in the 17th century, when Croatian mercenaries hired by King Louis XIII wore a cloth tied around their necks as part of their uniform. Louis liked the decorative look, so he brought it into Court dress and called it \"La Cravate\" to honour the Croatian soldiers. One thing led to another, and the necktie we know today evolved in the 1920\'s. \r\n\r\nOur neckties are handmade in sterling silver and we can paint them in any colour combination you\'d like. We\'re also working on a polka dot and bowtie version! Email tamara@studio1098.com if you\'d like to customize your colours!\r\n\r\n'),
(1826, 72, 0, 517, 'handmade, sterling silver, neck, tie, necktie, neckerchief, bowtie, bow tie, father\'s day, fathers day, dad, gift, anniversary, Homes First, Tie One On, jewellery, jewelry, custom, toronto, canada, stripes, stripe, polka dot, polka dots, tamara kronis, chantal desloges.'),
(1827, 62, 0, 517, 'The necktie probably entered into fashion history as a result of the 30 year war in France in the 17th century, when Croatian mercenaries hired by King Louis XIII wore a cloth tied around their necks as part of their uniform. Louis liked the decorative look, so he brought it into Court dress and called it \"La Cravate\" to honour the Croatian soldiers. One thing led to another, and the necktie we know today evolved in the 1920\'s. \r\n\r\nOur neckties are handmade in sterling silver and we can paint them in any colour combination you\'d like. We\'re also working on a polka dot and bowtie version! Email tamara@studio1098.com if you\'d like to customize your colours!'),
(1828, 61, 0, 518, '<div id=\"tabs\"><ul><li><a href=\"#tabs-1\"><h2>About Pink Sapphires</h2></a></li><li><a href=\"#tabs-2\"><h2>Design Notes</h2></a></li></ul>\r\n<div id=\"tabs-1\">\r\n<p>This beautifully proportioned sapphire engagement ring features an untreated natural 1.32 carat pink sapphire highlighted by a round brilliant diamond halo and set in white gold.&nbsp;</p>\r\n    <p>Proin elit arcu, rutrum commodo, vehicula tempus, commodo a, risus. Curabitur nec arcu. Donec sollicitudin mi sit amet mauris. Nam elementum quam ullamcorper ante. Etiam aliquet massa et lorem. Mauris dapibus lacus auctor risus. Aenean tempor ullamcorper leo. Vivamus sed magna quis ligula eleifend adipiscing. Duis orci. Aliquam sodales tortor vitae ipsum. Aliquam nulla. Duis aliquam molestie erat. Ut et mauris vel pede varius sollicitudin. Sed ut dolor nec orci tincidunt interdum. Phasellus ipsum. Nunc tristique tempus lectus.</p>\r\n<p>Pink sapphire gets its colour from the presence of the element chromium in it\'s growth matrix. The more chromium that is present in the environment in which it grows, the pinker it gets. If enough chromium is present, the sapphire becomes saturated enough with colour to be classified as a ruby, and if too much is present, the sapphire gets too dark and looks black. The chromium in this sapphire makes it almost magenta coloured.</p>\r\n  </div>\r\n  <div id=\"tabs-2\">\r\n<p>There are a few things that make this pink sapphire engagement ring special.&nbsp;The vibrant pink of the sapphire is definitely the focal point of this very bright ring. We like the fact that there are just a few small diamonds in the halo to set it off so that the pink of the sapphire isn\'t overwhelmed by the diamonds - too often jewellers add so many diamonds that they compete with the centre gemstone. The fact that this sapphire is untreated is also something that makes it special. Untreated sapphires are considered to be the most valuable, but often they aren\'t as vibrant in their colours. We were really excited when we found a pink sapphire that was both untreated and vivacious, and are really pleased with the sapphire engagement ring we made with it.&nbsp;</p>\r\n  </div>\r\n</div>'),
(1829, 72, 0, 518, 'cushion, cut, pink, sapphire, engagement, ring, diamond, halo, engagement ring, untreated, natural, sri lanka, custom, best, jewellery, jewelry, toronto, fine, tamara kronis'),
